      "action": "Petition the secular magistrate to formally recognize the Secular Merchants' Coalition as a legitimate commercial guild with standing to challenge the Shrine Auditors' Council's permit annulment in secular proceedings. The Wardens submit a formal brief documenting: (1) the Council's negligence in allowing the Lacquer Authority to copy consecrated seal templates, (2) the economic harm to 43+ market operators from the annulment, (3) the Coalition's de facto jurisdiction at Tower Bridge Concourse, and (4) the Council's failure to enforce their own annulment. The petition requests a preliminary injunction preventing the Council from threatening excommunication against Coalition members pending formal arbitration.",
      "outcome": "The secular magistrate, already skeptical of the Council's liturgical overreach into commercial affairs, agrees to hear the petition. After reviewing the Wardens' dossier — particularly the evidence of Council negligence — the magistrate issues a preliminary ruling: the Secular Merchants' Coalition is granted \"provisional guild status\" pending full review, which legally prohibits the Council from imposing religious sanctions on Coalition members for paying secular tariffs. The ruling does not overturn the annulment itself, but it strips the Council's most potent weapon: the threat of excommunication. The magistrate schedules a full arbitration hearing for the week before high-water season. The Council is furious but legally bound. The Signal-House Families take note — the Wardens now have the secular legal standing they previously lacked, making any future revenue-sharing negotiation a discussion between equals rather than supplicants. Coalition membership applications surge as operators who feared excommunication now have legal cover.",
      "targetLocation": "Tower Bridge Concourse",
      "tagChangeCount": 3,
      "chronicleEntryId": "a90d9af9-198e-44c1-b121-3108bc980eff"
    }
